 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub28.ezboard.com/uwilrowe.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Wilrowe</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0> at: 2/5/02 1:15:00 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub28.ezboard.com/uwilrowe.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Wilrowe</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>THogg's Lubba</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/5/02 1:08:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub28.ezboard.com/fdrinal28133frm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=444.topic&index=52>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Enchanters!</span><hr size=1> 1. I'm not going to turn this into a class balance issue because that is not why I'm replying.<br>
<br>
To Phaestus and Asanti: I am not denying the versatility of bards at all (song twisting).  On the contrary I would extol it since without it, the bard class would be extremely boring. <br>
<br>
From level's 1 thru...30 the bard class is way too powered.<br>
<br>
Why?<br>
<br>
Quite simply put, it's our songs. They are coded different than caster spells and they give the class it's sense of leniency. In PvP circumstances, it's a complete blowout. No other class from lvl's one to 40 can compensate as much technique as a bard can. <br>
<br>
You can argue and claim otherwise but it's true. Truth is: there is no class that can fear without the use of manna, mez without the use of manna, regen/hp without the use of manna, cast any magic based spells.  (Disregarding right-clicking items of course).  Again allow me to reiterate that I'm solely speaking for levels one thru 30/40<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> If the bard is increasing across levels in damage output from a song, and is also increasing across levels as far as melee damage, wouldn't this allow for curves of improvement for damage per second that more closely matched other curves? Wizards on that graph are only casting, same with druids, well shouldn't we then compare total possible bard damage output for a decent comparison. Likewise, let's consider the healing done by bards. During the time that a bard is providing some regen, aren't they also able to melee and/or help the group to take out mobs faster, therefore taking less damage (possible to consider this another form of healing)? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I concur completley.  No one is denying a bard's ability to heal or an enchanter's ability to haste.  The Breath of Harmony's effect Niv's Melody of Preservation can be taken into account as &quot;free&quot; hp regen as well and could possibly shift the graph upwards.  <br>
<br>
When I look at the graph, I don't take into account melee damage.  I see a comparison between, spell and song. A bards best nuke is an AoE nuke at 43.  Sadly it can only be used once, two at the most...that's it.  <br>
<br>
Take a look at the graph closely.  From level's one to seven a bard's nuking skill matches that of a wizard or druid.  As each classes's level increases their power increases.  Same goes for hp/regen ability and manna regen.  The resolution to this was...stacking ability.  Thott put it best:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Bards are marathon runners, casters are sprinters.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
That makes sense.  How about post level 30/40.  <br>
Velious expansion songs were a joke except for Occlusion of Sound. I think every bard still playing agrees with me on this one..including Aftathott.  <br>
<br>
Charm/fear/mez became capped... (Again, excluding pvp circumstances) and the graph once again shifts downwards. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
@ Asanti:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> It should be just as valid for every other class to complain because their versatility doesn’t increase along the same curve as the bard. Clerics, enchanters, rogues, warriors, wizards are all classes that focus on specialization. The higher the level, the more that specialization becomes evident.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I'm going to bite here and assume by versatility you mean stacking ability/song twisting.  From levels 1 to 30 yes, I would agree with you wholeheartedly. After 50, I would disagree. <br>
From Article:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Charm is wonderful at 27, too wonderful in fact, it should in my opinion be gimped, either by reducing its range or by having it require mana. Charm kiting is simply too powerful. It is my hope that the flat power curves are not left as they are as a punishment to the class for the 10 levels of charm kiting glory<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Generally what I found is that power for all classes rises proportional to level squared, except for bards. For bards power rises proportional to level. I did this analysis when after a long period of time playing I began to feel that bard power simply didn't improve equal to other classes. All the songs improved, and higher level ones were a bit better, but it just felt like the class as a whole wasn't improving properly. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Now with Luclin release, I'm sure anyone would agree it's a completely different story for not only bards but <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> all</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> classes.  Power graphs need to be calculated differently and with Alternate Advance points the story changes entirely. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> No other class comes close to the versatility of the bard. I’m sorry, but saying that you should be able to multi task like that, and be efficient too is just a bit much, don’t you think?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
What's wrong with being efficient?  Taking efficiency in its literal term...I agree.  Bards are extremly efficient. Than again so is every single class this game has to offer. To be brutally honest, I'm very pleased with the bard class as it stands for now.<br>
<br>
-Wilrowe<br>
Virtuoso (Retired)<br>
<br>
P.S. I don't know this for certain, but I don't think Thott's power curves were drawn to plead to VI/Sony for more &quot;efficiency, &quot; on the contrary I look at them as a means of calculation/communication between bards and other races in Everquest. <br>
<br>
Similarly, that was my intent behind showing the hyperlink. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
